FPP - Ch. 6 Exercises

Time Series Decomposition
Dan Hong | dnaeye@gmail.com

The following are my answers to the exercises in the excellent book Forecasting: Principles & Practice by Rob J Hyndman and George Athanasopoulos.

1. Show that a 3 x 5 MA is equivalent to a 7-term weighted moving average with weights of 0.067, 0.133, 0.200, 0.200, 0.200, 0.133, and 0.067.

\(y_{3x5} = \frac{1}{3}(Y_{t-1} + Y_t + Y_{t+1}) \ where\ Y_t = \frac{1}{5}(y_{t-2}+y_{t-1}+y_t+y_{t+1}+y_{t+2})\)

Therefore, \(y_{3+5} = \frac{1}{15}(y_{t-3} + 2y_{t-2} + 3y_{t-1} + 3y_t + 3y_{t+1} + 2y_{t+2} + y_{t+3})\)

The weights for the 7 terms are \(\frac{1}{15}\) (i.e., 0.067), \(\frac{2}{15}\) (i.e., 0.133), \(\frac{3}{15}\) (i.e., 0.200), \(\frac{3}{15}\) (i.e., 0.200), \(\frac{3}{15}\) (i.e., 0.200), \(\frac{2}{15}\) (i.e., 0.133), and , \(\frac{1}{15}\) (i.e., 0.067).

2. The plastics data set consists of the monthly sales (in thousands) of product A for a plastics manufacturer for five years.

2b. Plot the time series of sales of product A. Can you identify seasonal fluctuations and/or a trend-cycle?

autoplot(plastics)

There are annual seasonal fluctuations (each time period is a year) with peaks in the summer and troughs in the winter. Over the 5-year period, there is a positive trend.  

2b. Use a classical multiplicative decomposition to calculate the trend-cycle and seasonal indices.

plastics.dc <- decompose(plastics, type = "multiplicative")
plastics.dc %>% autoplot() + xlab("Year") + ggtitle("Classical multiplicative decomposition of plastics")

The seasonal indices range from 0.7 to 1.2, with the lowest in February and the highest in August. This means that sales are 0.7 x Trend (+ Remainder) in February and 1.2 x Trend (+ Remainder) in August.

2c. Do the results support the graphical interpretation from part a?

Yes, they do.

2d. Compute and plot the seasonally adjusted data.

plastics.sa <- plastics / plastics.dc$seasonal
autoplot(plastics.sa)

2e. Change one observation to be an outlier (e.g., add 500 to one observation), and recompute the seasonally adjusted data. What is the effect of the outlier?

plastics2 <- plastics
plastics2[24] <- plastics[24] + 500
plastics2.dc <- decompose(plastics2, type = "multiplicative")
plastics2.sa <- plastics2 / plastics2.dc$seasonal
autoplot(plastics2.sa)

Creating the outlier created a spike in the plot of the seasonally adjusted data at month 24, which was the December of year 2. In the seasonal and trend plots, the effect is slightly diminished, but there is still a noticeable disruption when compared to the decomposition plots of the original decomposed data.

2f. Does it make any difference if the outlier is near the end rather than in the middle of the time series?

plastics3 <- plastics
plastics3[4] <- plastics[4] + 500
plastics3.dc <- decompose(plastics3, type = "multiplicative")
plastics3.sa <- plastics3 / plastics3.dc$seasonal
autoplot(plastics3.sa)

In the seasonally adjusted plot, the spike seems more pronounced. In terms of the seasonal plot, the effect is barely noticeable; but there is a slight bump up in the trend plot at the start of the plot.

3. Recall your retail time series data (from Exercise 3 in Section 2.10). Decompose the series using X11. Does it reveal any outliers, or unusual features that you had not noticed previously?

retaildata <- readxl::read_excel("retail.xlsx", skip=1)
myts <- ts(retaildata[,"A3349873A"], frequency=12, 
           start=c(1982,4))
library(seasonal)
retail.dc <- seas(myts, x11="")
autoplot(retail.dc)

The remainder plot charts noise in the data, and the largest peak was in 2000, which broke from the seasonal and trend-cycle behavior.

4. Figures 6.16 and 6.17 show the result of decomposing the number of persons in the civilian labour force in Australia each month from February 1978 to August 1995.

4a. Write about 3–5 sentences describing the results of the decomposition. Pay particular attention to the scales of the graphs in making your interpretation.

There is a general upward trend, indicating that the labor force is growing. Although there seems to be increasing variance in the seasonal plot, the scale indicates that the trend is relatively small when compared to the scale of the overall trend. On the other hand, the monthly plot shows varying monthly trends – some months experienced growth (e.g., July, September, December), while others experienced declines (e.g., March, August, November). The remainder plot shows that there was a huge drop in the early 1990s.

4b. Is the recession of 1991/1992 visible in the estimated components?

Yes, the remainder plot shows that those years were negative outliers, with drops as low as 400.

5. This exercise uses the cangas data (monthly Canadian gas production in billions of cubic metres, January 1960 – February 2005).

5a. Plot the data using autoplot(), ggsubseriesplot() and ggseasonplot() to look at the effect of the changing seasonality over time. What do you think is causing it to change so much?

autoplot(cangas)

ggsubseriesplot(cangas)

ggseasonplot(cangas)

The autoplot graph shows that the differences between seasons have changed over time, while the ggsubseriesplot demonstrates that each month is different, with the average annual highs in the winter months and the average lows in the summer months. The ggseasonplot shows that overall gas production has increased over time and also that seasonal variations have grown more extreme.

5b. Do an STL decomposition of the data. You will need to choose s.window to allow for the changing shape of the seasonal component.

cangas %>% stl(s.window = "periodic", robust=TRUE) %>% autoplot()

5c. Compare the results with those obtained using SEATS and X11. How are they different?

library(seasonal)
cangas %>% seas() %>% autoplot() + ggtitle("SEATS Decomposition of Canadian Gas Production")

cangas %>% seas(x11="") %>% autoplot() + ggtitle("X11 Decomposition of Canadian Gas Production")

While the seasonal pattern looks the same, the trend and remainder plots from the X11 decomposition method appear less noisy and smoother.

6. We will use the bricksq data (Australian quarterly clay brick production. 1956–1994) for this exercise.

6a. Use an STL decomposition to calculate the trend-cycle and seasonal indices. (Experiment with having fixed or changing seasonality.)

bricksq %>% stl(s.window="periodic", robust=TRUE) %>% autoplot() + ggtitle("STL Decomposition of bricksq with Fixed Seasonality")

bricksq %>% stl(s.window=6, robust=TRUE) %>% autoplot() + ggtitle("STL Decomposition of bricksq with Changing Seasonality")

6b. Compute and plot the seasonally adjusted data.

bricksq %>% stl(s.window="periodic", robust=TRUE) %>% seasadj() %>% autoplot()

6c. Use a naïve method to produce forecasts of the seasonally adjusted data.

bricksq.nonrobust <- stl(bricksq, s.window = "periodic", robust = FALSE)
bricksq.nonrobust %>% seasadj() %>% naive() %>% autoplot() + ggtitle("Naive Forecast of bricksq with Non-Robust Decomposition")

6d. Use stlf() to reseasonalise the results, giving forecasts for the original data.

bricksq.rs <- stlf(bricksq, method='naive')
forecast(bricksq.rs, h=8)

6e. Do the residuals look uncorrelated?

checkresiduals(bricksq.rs)

Based on the ACF plot, the data appears mostly uncorrelated, except at lags (i.e., quarters) 5 and 8.

6f. Repeat with a robust STL decomposition. Does it make much difference?

bricksq.robust <- stl(bricksq, s.window="periodic", robust=TRUE)
bricksq.robust %>% seasadj() %>% naive() %>% autoplot() + ggtitle("Naive Forecast of bricksq with Robust Decomposition")

The plots appear to be very similar. To verify that they are similar:

naive(seasadj(bricksq.robust))$mean

The difference between the two forecast methods is 2.402805. In other words, the robust forecast is just 0.51% larger than the non-robust method.

6g. Compare forecasts from stlf() with those from snaive(), using a test set comprising the last 2 years of data. Which is better?

bricks.train <- window(bricksq, end=c(1992,4))
bricks.test <- window(bricksq, start=c(1993,1))
bricks.stlf <- stlf(bricks.train)
bricks.snaive <- snaive(bricks.train)
fcast.stlf <- forecast(bricks.stlf, h=7)
fcast.snaive <- forecast(bricks.snaive, h=7)
res.stlf <- as.numeric(bricks.test) - fcast.stlf$mean
res.snaive <- as.numeric(bricks.test) - fcast.snaive$mean
ts.plot(res.stlf, res.snaive, gpars = list(xlab="Year", ylab="Residual", col=c("red","blue")))
legend("bottomright", legend=c("STLF","SNaive"), col=c("red","blue"), cex=0.5, lty=1)

Overall, the stlf method produced better forecasts (i.e., smaller residuals with actual test data): a mean residual of 32.022682 vs. that of 34.2857143 for snaive, an improvement of 6.6%.

7. Use stlf() to produce forecasts of the writing series with either method='naive' or method='rwdrift', whichever is most appropriate. Use the lambda argument if you think a Box-Cox transformation is required.

autoplot(writing)

writing.dc <- decompose(writing, type = "multiplicative")
writing.dc %>% autoplot() + ggtitle("Classical multiplicative decomposition of writing dataset")

The seasonal pattern looks very stable, but just to verify, we should run the automated Box-Cox lambda function.

bcl <- BoxCox.lambda(writing)
bcl
[1] 0.1557392

The function indicates that a small Box-Cox transformation is recommended.

writing.train <- window(writing, end=c(1975,12))
writing.test <- window(writing, start=c(1976,1))
writing.naive <- stlf(writing.train, method='naive', lambda=bcl)
fcast.naive <- forecast(writing.naive, h=24)
writing.drift <- stlf(writing.train, method='rwdrift', lambda=bcl)
fcast.drift <- forecast(writing.drift, h=24)
writing.res.naive <- as.numeric(writing.test) - fcast.naive$mean
writing.res.drift <- as.numeric(writing.test) - fcast.drift$mean
ts.plot(writing.res.naive, writing.res.drift, gpars = list(xlab="Year", ylab="Residual", col=c("red","blue")))
legend("bottomright", legend=c("Naive","Drift"), col=c("red","blue"), cex=0.5, lty=1)

abs(mean(writing.res.naive))
[1] 81.04883
abs(mean(writing.res.drift))
[1] 44.32244

Both methods performed similarly, but the rwdrift method performed 45.31% better.

8. Use stlf() to produce forecasts of the fancy series with either method='naive' or method='rwdrift', whichever is most appropriate. Use the lambda argument if you think a Box-Cox transformation is required.

autoplot(fancy)

fancy.dc <- decompose(fancy, type = "multiplicative")
fancy.dc %>% autoplot() + ggtitle("Classical multiplicative decomposition of fancy dataset")

The seasonal variation appears stable, but we should validate this by running the automated Box-Cox lambda function.

bcl <- BoxCox.lambda(fancy)
bcl
[1] 0.002127317

The function verifies the assumption that no transformation is required.

fancy.train <- window(fancy, end=c(1991,12))
fancy.test <- window(fancy, start=c(1992,1))
fancy.naive <- stlf(fancy.train, method='naive')
fcast.naive <- forecast(fancy.naive, h=24)
fancy.drift <- stlf(fancy.train, method='rwdrift')
fcast.drift <- forecast(fancy.drift, h=24)
fancy.res.naive <- as.numeric(fancy.test) - fcast.naive$mean
fancy.res.drift <- as.numeric(fancy.test) - fcast.drift$mean
ts.plot(fancy.res.naive, fancy.res.drift, gpars = list(xlab="Year", ylab="Residual", col=c("red","blue")))
legend("bottomright", legend=c("Naive","Drift"), col=c("red","blue"), cex=0.5, lty=1)

abs(mean(fancy.res.naive))
[1] 2601.172
abs(mean(fancy.res.drift))
[1] 1117.606

Both methods performed similarly, but the rwdrift method performed 57.03% better.
